st year, Madam\nSpeaker, but apparently this government's cuts have not. ","index":"00273","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� This\nis the opportunity that this government had to invest in this province, to\ninvest and put people back to work, and yet this Infrastructure Minister won't\neven stand up to defend his underspending year over year over year. It's the\nsame tired minister with the same tired notes talking about the same tired\nplan. These are promises that are going to be broken. ","index":"00274","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Why\nwon't this government simply admit that they're going to underspend this year\nthe same as they do every year? ","index":"00275","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Oh, oh.","index":"00276","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> I just feel I have to just make a mention that banging on the\ndesks is considered a bit of a health hazard to our translators and to Hansard\nthat have to be listening to this very carefully. And because our mics are so\nsensitive, that noise is quite a detriment. ","index":"00277","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So I'm\nasking people again�or, reminding people that it would be a great idea not to\nbang on desks. ","index":"00278","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Ron </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337213\">Schuler</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Infrastructure):</b> Well, Madam Speaker, I'd like to thank the member for\nConcordia for asking a finance question and the Finance Minister allowing me to\nanswer it. ","index":"00279","speaker":"Ron Schuler"},{"html":"����� Madam\nSpeaker, in 2021-2022, our government's committed to spending\n$500&nbsp;million; 2022-2023: $500&nbsp;million; 2023-24: $500&nbsp;million.\nThat is $1.5&nbsp;million over three years. ","index":"00280","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Let's\ncompare that to the NDP, Madam Speaker:: 2000-2001, $98&nbsp;million; '01-02,\n$93&nbsp;million; '02-03, $111&nbsp;million. They didn't spend in one year what\nwe're�<i>[interjection]</i>�they didn't spend in three�<i>[interjection]</i>�what\nwe're spending in one�$1.5&nbsp;billion. ","index":"00281","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Hold\nonto your seat. Move your Lexus. Move your Beemers. We're building this\nprovince. ","index":"00282","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDougald </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337215\">Lamont</a></b><b>�(St.\nBoniface):</b> On Monday, this government told Manitobans to drive through a\nblizzard to a vaccine clinic in Steinbach that was closed. They received\nmultiple reminders despite the cancellation. ","index":"00283","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"����� We\nchecked the vaccine appointment line and we were told that they were working\nwith PetalMD, a Quebec-based company whose website shows they're providing\nservices to the Manitoba government. We've heard these operators aren't trained\nand are working in call centres in other provinces, which would certainly\nexplain why they don't know the difference between Morris and Morden or\nStonewall and Steinbach and why they're telling Manitobans to drive over icy\nhighways in a blizzard to clinics that have been shut down.","index":"00284","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Is\nthis latest life-threatening snafu because this government outsourced calling\nto an out-of-province company to save a few bucks? ","index":"00285","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nBrian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337216\">Pallister</a></b><b>�(Premier):</b> I can only suggest to the member that, if the federal\ngovernment had provided us with more vaccines across this country, we wouldn't\nbe ranking in 40th place, as we are right&nbsp;&nbsp;now; we'd have a lot fewer\ncasualties as a consequence of the COVID pandemic; people would be healthier\nand feeling better about our recovery; but they didn't do that. ","index":"00286","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� And so\nI would just simply remind the member that right across this great country\nthere are teams of people working diligently to distribute vaccines as fast as\nthey can, as best they can, but we'd all love to have a lot more. ","index":"00287","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The honourable member for St.&nbsp;Boniface, on a supplementary\nquestion. ","index":"00288","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDougald </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337218\">Lamont</a></b><b>�(St. Boniface):</b> Still on vaccines: I've been getting emails from\nconstituents who are wondering why police are not on the priority list for\nvaccines. As one constituent�a teacher�wrote, quote, firefighters and\nparamedics have rightfully received vaccines as emergency personnel. Police are\nenforcing health orders, respond to emergency calls, deal with people in crisis\nand often accompany people to hospitals. End quote. ","index":"00289","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"����� I wrote to the Minister of Health, who wrote back saying the\ngovernment is following the National Advisory Committee on Immunization, or\nNACI. But NACI's guide�which I table�has first responders, police and\nfirefighters all in the same group in stage two. ","index":"00290","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Why is\nthis government ignoring the national vaccine priority recommendations they say\nthey're following? Are police front-line responders or not? ","index":"00291","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nBrian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337219\">Pallister</a></b><b>�(Premier):</b>\nOur government is respecting the recommendations of our health leaders\nthroughout this pandemic; we'll continue to do that. ","index":"00292","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� I\nwould encourage all of us to make sure and give our support and encouragement\nto these folks who are undertaking an historic task, not just the health\nleadership, in terms of Dr. Roussin and his team, but also the vaccine team.\nThis is an incredibly stressful time for them�as if it for all of us�but they\nhave undertaken to do something that's never ever been done before in the\nhistory of this province. ","index":"00293","speaker":""},{"html":"����� It's a\nlot harder than running a newspaper, for example, or being in opposition. ","index":"00294","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Jon </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337221\">Gerrard</a></b><b>�(River Heights):</b> Yes. Madam Speaker, last week, the Minister of\nHealth asked me to write to her with personal concerns which are brought to me.\n","index":"00295","speaker":"Jon Gerrard"},{"html":"����� My question today is about a person who's very disabled and needs home\ncare. The concern is so serious I have written five times to the minister\nduring the last several weeks, yet there has been no action. Since March 26,\nshe's been suffering and unable even to have a bath because she's been without\nthe home care she so desperately needs. This woman has written to the\nOmbudsman, has filed a human rights appeal. ","index":"00296","speaker":""},{"html":"����� When\nwill the minister make sure Manitoba's home-care system is working properly so\nthis woman can get the home care she needs? ","index":"00297","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nHeather </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337222\">Stefanson</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Health and Seniors Care):</b> Certainly we are aware of the issue, and I\nknow that I've asked our department to look into this and work with this\nindividual to ensure that she gets the home care that she needs. ","index":"00298","speaker":"Heather Stefanson"},{"html":"����� We\nwant to ensure that all Manitobans get the appropriate care that they need in\ntheir homes, in their&nbsp;&nbsp;communities and wherever they live, Madam\nSpeaker. And I know that our officials will work diligently with this\nindividual to ensure that the situation is rectified. ","index":"00299","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms.\nJanice </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69337224\">Morley-Lecomte</a></b><b>�(Seine\nRiver):</b> We know that our government is committed to ensuring services\nthroughout the province are accessible and inclusive to all Manitobans. ","in